result.execSummary:
The defendant CHRISTOPHER D ENK was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Obstructing an Officer, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

9:24 AM Defendant CHRISTOPHER D ENK appeared in court, Attorney Gerise Marie Laspisa appeared in court for State of Wisconsin. Defendant confirms receipt of the criminal complaint and waives reading. Court instructs the defendant of the maximum penalty on each count. Court finds probable cause. Court instructs the defendant of his/her right to an attorney. Defendant enters a plea of NO CONTEST. Court instructs defendant of his/her right to counsel. Defendant waives right to counsel. Court accepts waiver. DA Laspisa recites offer - fine and costs and DNA. Defendant changes plea to GUILTY.

Court goes over constitutional rights with the defendant - defendant waives these rights. Court goes over the elements of each offense. Court instructs defendant of the maximum penalty. Court instructs defendant regarding deportation. 

Defendant enters a plea of GUILTY. Court finds the plea is made knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently. Court finds there is a factual basis to support the plea. Court finds the defendant guilty as charged. Court orders the judgment of conviction be entered here today. Sentencing statement by DA Laspisa. Statement by the defendant. Statement by the Court.

Court sentences the defendant to:

-5 days in jail. Sentence is to commence within 60 days.  Court grants huber, out-of-county service and out-of-county travel. 
-Court cost. Court grants the defendant 60 days to pay or call the Clerk of Courts Office (920-294-4142) to set-up a payment plan. 
-Defendant is to submit a DNA Sample. 

+Defendant is to complete processing with the Green Lake County Sheriff's Department. 

Court adjourned at 9:34 AM.
Initial appearance on February 8, 2022 at 09:30 am. / Def was mailed a copy of the criminal complaint.

Def called upset because his girlfriend informed him he had a warrant for his missed court date this morning. Def stated he never received anything about this court date and didn't know he had one today. Def questioned the address we had on file and stated that address was incorrect. Def's address was updated. Def was given a new court date of Feb 08, 2022 at 9:30 AM. Def was very appreciative. Def was told he'd be mailed a copy of his criminal complaint and to stop at the Clerk of Court's Office before his court date if it wasn't received in the mail in time.
